</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3616553FF90AF3ED18ADE7BFD28120A" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BC436D8FF90AF3ED18ADE7BFD28120A" blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="B90FEACAFF90AF3ED18ADE7BFECF1271" bold="true" box="[198,361,271,297]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Distribution:</emphasis>
Central, northern and northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F36C7648FF90AF3ED255DE64FC361272" box="[793,912,272,298]" name="Argentina" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, occupying about the Southern 
<collectingRegion id="49BFF83AFF90AF3ED445DE64FF6E120A" country="Argentina" name="Chaco" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Chaco province</collectingRegion>
of the Chacoan subgregion (
<figureCitation id="13402A5DFF90AF3ED356DE4CFD27120A" box="[538,641,312,338]" captionStart="FIGURES 107–108" captionStartId="69.[151,269,1969,1993]" captionTargetBox="[166,1417,182,1945]" captionTargetId="figure-37@69.[166,1420,182,1945]" captionTargetPageId="69" captionText="FIGURES 107–108. Distribution maps. 107. Genieridium medinae (circles) and G. bordoni (triangles); 108. Nunoidium argentinum (circles), Pereiraidium almeidai (squares) and Silvinha unica (triangles)." pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3616553FF90AF3ED18ADE2BFD4A111A" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC436D8FF90AF3ED18ADE2BFE271142" blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="B90FEACAFF90AF3ED18ADE2BFEE71221" bold="true" box="[198,321,351,377]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D5BFF90AF3ED005DE14FE6D1221" authorityName="Vaz-De-Mello" authorityYear="2008" box="[329,459,352,377]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Nunoidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEACAFF90AF3ED005DE14FE6D1221" box="[329,459,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Nunoidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D5BFF90AF3ED20DDE14FC731221" authorityName="Vaz-De-Mello" authorityYear="2008" box="[833,981,352,377]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Genieridium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90FEACAFF90AF3ED20DDE14FC731221" box="[833,981,352,377]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Genieridium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, the completeness of the carina separating pronotal disc from hypomeron, vertical pygidial position, and presence of posterior pronotal bead, among other characters, will readily separate it. Apomorphies of this genus are the presence of posterior pronotal bead, absence of modification in male claws, elongation of spermatheca, and psammophilous modifications of metalegs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436D8FF90AF3ED18ADD53FD4A111A" blockId="36.[151,1436,151,617]" box="[198,748,551,578]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis id="B90FEACAFF90AF3ED18ADD53FEC91119" bold="true" box="[198,367,551,577]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Composition:</emphasis>
Only the 
<typeStatus id="54C0887AFF90AF3ED0A8DD5CFDB0111A" box="[484,534,552,578]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">type</typeStatus>
species is known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
